**Solution Explanation**

For a set of points the farthest two points are always vertices of the
convex hull of the set.  
Therefore the task reduces to

1. build the convex hull of all given points,
2. find the pair of hull vertices that are farthest apart  
   (the *diameter* of the hull).

The distance between two points  
`(x1 , y1)` and `(x2 , y2)` is

```
d = sqrt( (x1 – x2)² + (y1 – y2)² )
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### 1.  Convex hull – monotone chain

* sort all points by `x` (and by `y` if `x` is equal)
* build the lower hull  
  (walk through the sorted list, keep the last two points of the hull
  and the current point, pop the middle one while the turn is not
  counter‑clockwise)
* build the upper hull in the same way, walking from the end of the
  sorted list to the beginning
* concatenate lower and upper hulls (the last point of each part is
  omitted to avoid duplication)

The algorithm runs in `O(n log n)` because of the sorting step.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### 2.  Diameter – rotating calipers

Let the hull contain `m` vertices `p[0] … p[m‑1]` in counter‑clockwise
order.

```
i = 0, j = 1
while i < m
        while area(p[i], p[i+1], p[j+1]) > area(p[i], p[i+1], p[j])
                j = (j + 1) mod m
        update answer with distance(p[i], p[j])
        i = i + 1
```

The area test is equivalent to checking whether the distance from the
edge `p[i]p[i+1]` to the point `p[j+1]` is larger than the distance to
`p[j]`.  
The whole procedure is linear in the number of hull vertices (`O(m)`).

--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### 3.  Correctness Proof  

We prove that the algorithm outputs the maximum Euclidean distance
between any two points of the input set.

---

##### Lemma 1  
For any set of points the farthest pair of points lies on the convex
hull of the set.

**Proof.**

Assume a farthest pair `A,B` is not on the hull.  
Then at least one of them lies inside the convex hull.  
The convex hull is the intersection of all half‑planes that contain
the set, thus the segment `AB` is completely inside the hull.
Consequently there exists a point `C` on the hull that is farther from
`A` (or from `B`) than `B` is from `A`, contradicting the choice of
`A,B`. ∎



##### Lemma 2  
The monotone chain algorithm returns the vertices of the convex hull
in counter‑clockwise order.

**Proof.**

The algorithm is a standard implementation of the monotone chain
construction.  
During the construction of the lower (upper) hull we always keep the
last two points of the current hull and the new point.  
If the three points make a non‑counter‑clockwise turn, the middle one
cannot belong to the convex hull and is removed.  
After processing all points the remaining sequence is the lower (upper)
hull.  
Concatenating both parts gives all hull vertices exactly once and in
counter‑clockwise order. ∎



##### Lemma 3  
During the rotating calipers loop, for each edge `p[i]p[i+1]` the index
`j` is the farthest vertex from that edge.

**Proof.**

The loop invariant is that `j` is the vertex that maximizes the
distance to the current edge.  
When moving from edge `p[i]p[i+1]` to the next edge `p[i+1]p[i+2]`,
the farthest vertex can only stay the same or move forward along the
hull.  
The inner `while` loop advances `j` while the area (i.e. the distance
to the edge) increases, thus after it terminates `j` is the farthest
vertex for the current edge. ∎



##### Lemma 4  
The algorithm considers every pair of hull vertices that can be a
diameter.

**Proof.**

For each edge `p[i]p[i+1]` the algorithm checks the distance between
`p[i]` and the farthest vertex `p[j]` from that edge (Lemma&nbsp;3).
Any diameter pair must be antipodal: the two vertices are farthest
apart and lie on opposite sides of the hull.  
Such a pair is examined when the algorithm processes the edge that is
adjacent to one of the two vertices.  
Therefore every possible diameter pair is evaluated. ∎



##### Theorem  
The algorithm outputs the maximum Euclidean distance between any two
points of the input set.

**Proof.**

By Lemma&nbsp;1 the maximum distance is attained by a pair of hull
vertices.  
By Lemma&nbsp;4 the algorithm evaluates the distance of every
candidate pair.  
The algorithm keeps the maximum of all evaluated distances, hence the
final value equals the true maximum distance. ∎



--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### 4.  Complexity Analysis

Let `n` be the number of input points and `m` the number of hull
vertices (`m ≤ n`).

*Sorting* – `O(n log n)`  
*Hull construction* – `O(n)`  
*Rotating calipers* – `O(m)`  

Overall time complexity: **`O(n log n)`**  
Memory consumption: the list of points and the hull – **`O(n)`**.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

#### 5.  Reference Implementation  (C++17)

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

struct Point {
    double x, y;
    bool operator<(const Point& other) const {
        if (x != other.x) return x < other.x;
        return y < other.y;
    }
};

double cross(const Point& O, const Point& A, const Point& B) {
    return (A.x - O.x) * (B.y - O.y) - (A.y - O.y) * (B.x - O.x);
}

double dist2(const Point& A, const Point& B) {
    double dx = A.x - B.x, dy = A.y - B.y;
    return dx * dx + dy * dy;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    if (!(cin >> n)) return 0;
    vector<Point> pts(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) cin >> pts[i].x >> pts[i].y;

    if (n == 0) {
        cout << "Final Answer: 0\n";
        return 0;
    }

    sort(pts.begin(), pts.end());
    vector<Point> hull;

    // lower hull
    for (const auto& p : pts) {
        while (hull.size() >= 2 &&
               cross(hull[hull.size()-2], hull.back(), p) <= 0)
            hull.pop_back();
        hull.push_back(p);
    }
    // upper hull
    size_t t = hull.size() + 1;
    for (int i = n-2; i >= 0; --i) {
        const auto& p = pts[i];
        while (hull.size() >= t &&
               cross(hull[hull.size()-2], hull.back(), p) <= 0)
            hull.pop_back();
        hull.push_back(p);
    }
    if (hull.size() > 1) hull.pop_back(); // last point == first point

    int m = hull.size();
    if (m == 1) {
        cout << "Final Answer: 0\n";
        return 0;
    }
    if (m == 2) {
        double d = sqrt(dist2(hull[0], hull[1]));
        cout << "Final Answer: " << fixed << setprecision(6) << d << "\n";
        return 0;
    }

    // rotating calipers
    double best = 0.0;
    int j = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
        int ni = (i + 1) % m;
        // move j while area increases
        while (true) {
            int nj = (j + 1) % m;
            double cur = fabs(cross(hull[i], hull[ni], hull[j]));
            double nxt = fabs(cross(hull[i], hull[ni], hull[nj]));
            if (nxt > cur) j = nj;
            else break;
        }
        double d2 = dist2(hull[i], hull[j]);
        if (d2 > best) best = d2;
    }

    cout << "Final Answer: " << fixed << setprecision(6) << sqrt(best) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

The program follows exactly the algorithm proven correct above and
conforms to the required output format.

